    "leafs": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Maple Leafs",
      "league": "NHL",
      "record": "32-36-14",
      "detail": "8th in Atlantic Division",
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The Toronto Maple Leafs' season ended not with a bang but with a whimper - a seven-game losing streak that turned the final weeks into an autopsy. <strong>With a 32-36-14 record and just 78 points, the Leafs finished 8th in the Atlantic Division, 31 games behind the pace, their playoff hopes extinguished before May even arrived.</strong> This wasn't a collapse; it was a slow-motion failure, the kind that demands answers management can't dodge.\n\nThe numbers tell a damning story. A losing record in a league where mediocrity still gets you a lottery ticket. Fifteen seeds don't win anything, and the Leafs' front office knows it. Now comes the reckoning - coaching decisions loom, the draft lottery beckons, and the salary cap ceiling presses down like a coffin lid. Free agency will demand ruthlessness: which veterans stay, which get moved, and whether this core can be salvaged or needs dismantling.\n\n<strong>The offseason won't be quiet in Toronto. Fans expect answers, and management will have to provide them - or face the consequences in October.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated May 1, 2026"
      },
