    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "14-17",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays' early-season promise sputtered into frustration Thursday night, their bats silenced in a <strong>1-7 drubbing by the Twins</strong> that snapped a brief two-game surge and left them grasping at momentum. At 14-17, they're mired in fourth in the AL East, 6 games back and nursing a one-game skid - a far cry from the contender buzz that once hummed around this roster. Vladimir Guerrero Jr. stood tall with a solo homer in the loss, his.285 average anchoring an offense that's averaged just 2.3 runs over the last skid, but the bullpen melted down again, coughing up six runs after the fifth. No major injuries surfaced, though the rotation's depth remains a nagging worry with Kevin Gausman nursing a tweak. This club's trajectory screams mediocrity unless the lineup awakens - they're 10th in the playoff pecking order for a reason. <strong>Saturday's rubber match at Minnesota looms large at 7:10 PM ET</strong>: win it, and they steal a series from a surging Twins squad; fold, and the AL East graveyard beckons deeper. Jays Nation, time to roar or resign to another also-ran summer.",
        "updated": "Updated May 1, 2026"
      },
